-taiwan.org/PT]\n|-\n|{{RUS}}|| Representative Office in Moscow for the Taipei-Moscow Economic and Cultural Coordination Commission || [[Chen Chun-shen]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/RU]\n|-\n|{{SAU}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]] || [[Lin Jinn-jong]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/SA]\n|-\n|{{SIN}}|| [[Taipei Representative Office in Singapore]] || [[Francis Liang]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/SG]\n|-\n|{{SVK}}|| Taipei Representative Office, Bratislava || Andrew Chang || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/sk]\n|-\n|{{ZAF}}|| [[Taipei Liaison Office in the Republic of South Africa]] || [[Matthew Chou]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/ZA]\n|-\n|{{KOR}}|| [[Taipei Mission in Korea]] || Daniel Diann-wen Tang || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/KR]\n|-\n|{{ESP}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Spain|Oficina Econ\u00f3mica y Cultural de Taipei]] || [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Liu]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/ES]\n|-\n|{{SWE}}|| [[Taipei Mission in Sweden]] || [[Daniel Liao]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/SE]\n|-\n|{{SUI}}|| Taipei Cultural and Economic Delegation in Switzerland || [[Liu Bang-zyh]] || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/CH]\n|-\n|{{THA}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Thailand]] || [[Tung Chen-yuan]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/TH]\n|-\n|{{TUR}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Mission in Ankara]] || James Chen || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/TR]\n|-\n|{{UAE}}|| The Commercial Office of Taipei || [[Chang Wang-lu]] || [http://www.roc-taiwan.org/DXB]\n|-\n|{{GBR}}|| [[Taipei Representative Office in the U.K.]] || [[David Y. L. Lin|David Lin]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/UK]\n|-\n|{{USA}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in the United States]] || [[Stanley Kao]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/US]\n|-\n|{{VNM}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Vietnam]] || [[Richard R. C. Shih]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/VN]\n|}\n\n== Former representative offices ==\n*{{flag|Bangladesh}} - Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Bangladesh (closed in 2009, transferred to [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Center in India]] and [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Thailand]])\n*{{flag|Bolivia}} - Taipei Economic Office in [[La Paz]] (closed in 2009, transferred to [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Argentina]])\n*{{flag|Guam}} (suspended in 2017, transferred to Embassy of the Republic of China in [[Palau]])\n*{{flag|Libya}} - [[Taiwan Commercial Office in Tripoli]] (closed in 2011, transferred to Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Jordan)\n*{{flag|Norway}} - [[Taipei Representative Office in Norway]] (closed in 2017, transferred to [[Taipei Mission in Sweden]])\n*{{flag|Uruguay}} - Taipei Economic Office in [[Montevideo]] (closed, transferred to [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Argentina]])\n*{{flag|Venezuela}} - Taipei Economic Office in [[Caracas]] (closed in 2009, transferred to [[Taipei Commercial Office in Bogot\u00e1, Colombia]])\n\n==See also==\n* [[Foreign relations of the Republic of China]]\n* [[Political status of Taiwan]]\n* [[Chinese Taipei]]\n* [[Hong Kong Economic and Trade Office]]\n* [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Canada]]\n* [[List of diplomatic missions of Taiwan]]\n* [[Timeline of diplomatic relations of the Republic of China]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080424074047/http://www.taiwanembassy.org/mp.asp?mp=1 Overseas Office Republic of China (Taiwan)]\n*[http://www.boca.gov.tw/mp?mp=2 Bureau of Consular Affairs, Republic of China (Taiwan)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080622005317/http://www.cieca.org.tw/DB/english_web/index.asp Chinese International Economic Association Cooperation]\n\n{{Diplomatic missions of the Republic of China}}\n{{Foreign relations of Taiwan}}\n\n[[Category:Politics of the Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Taipei Economic and Cultural Offices]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|''De facto'' embassy of Taiwan}}{{Infobox Chinese\n|pic=Trouk.jpg\n|picsize=\n|piccap=[[Representative of Taiwan, London|Taipei Representative Office in the U.K.]] in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]].\n|showflag=cp\n|t=\u81fa\u5317\u7d93\u6fdf\u6587\u5316\u8fa6\u4e8b\u8655\n|s=\u53f0\u5317\u7ecf\u6d4e\u6587\u5316\u529e\u4e8b\u5904\n|p=T\u00e1ib\u011bi J\u012bngj\u00ec W\u00e9nh\u00f9a B\u00e0nsh\u00ecch\u00f9\n|myr=T\u00e1ib\u011bi J\u01d0ngj\u00ec W\u00e9nhw\u00e0 B\u00e0nshr\u0300ch\u00f9\n|tp=T\u00e1ib\u011bi J\u01d0ngj\u00ec W\u00fanh\u00f9a B\u00e0nsh\u00echch\u00f9\n|w=T'aipei Chingchi Wenhua Panshihch'u\n|poj=T\u00e2i-pak Keng-ch\u00e8 B\u00fbn-h\u00f2a P\u0101n-s\u016b-chh\u00f9 \n}}\n\nThe '''Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office''' ('''TECRO'''), also known as '''Taipei Economic and Cultural Office''' ('''TECO''') or '''Taipei Representative Office''' ('''TRO'''), is an alternative to an [[embassy]] or a [[consulate]] which handles the foreign affairs and citizen services of the [[Republic of China]] (Taiwan) in countries that have diplomatic relations with the [[People's Republic of China]] (PRC, commonly \"China\"). Under the terms of the [[One China Policy]] stipulated by the PRC, such countries may not have diplomatic relations with the Republic of China, as the PRC denies the status of ROC as a [[sovereign state]] and claims Taiwan as part of its territory. As a result, these countries do not allow the ROC to establish an \"official\" embassy or consulate but instead allow the ROC to establish these representative offices to conduct unofficial government relations with the host countries.\n\nExcept in the United States and Japan, these establishments use the term \"[[Taipei]]\" instead of \"[[Taiwan]]\", \"ROC\" or even the term \"Nationalist China\" (named after the ruling party [[Kuomintang]]) since the term \"Taipei\" avoids implying that Taiwan is a different country on a par with the PRC or that there are \"[[Two Chinas]]\", the PRC and the ROC, both of which would cause difficulties for their host countries.{{citation needed|reason=This whole paragraph needs a citation.|date=May 2018}}\n\nTECROs state that their aim is \"to promote bilateral trade, investment, culture, science and technology exchanges and cooperation, as well as better understanding\", although they perform many of the same functions as an [[embassy]] or [[consulate general]], such as issuing visas and [[Republic of China passport|passports]]. In this respect, they function as [[De facto embassy|''de facto'' embassies]].\n\nTECROs in the [[United States]] enjoy many diplomatic privileges such as [[extraterritoriality]], providing [[consular assistance|consular protection]] and their staff have [[diplomatic immunity]].<ref>[http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/intl-community/2013/02/06/369736/US-diplomatic.htm New US diplomatic immunity pact a breakthrough: MOFA], ''[[The China Post]]'', February 6, 2013</ref>  Other countries also establish reciprocal representative offices in Taiwan, such as the [[American Institute in Taiwan]], [[Canadian Trade Office in Taipei]] and [[Japan\u2013Taiwan Exchange Association]].\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Chinese Civil War}}\nFollowing the admission of the PRC to the [[United Nations]] in 1971, many countries began to establish diplomatic relations with the government in [[Beijing]], and as a consequence, ended diplomatic relations with the ROC Government in [[Taipei]].<ref name=\"Taiwan Review\">[http://taiwantoday.tw/ct.asp?xItem=758&ctNode=2198&mp=9 The Road Less Traveled], ''[[Taiwan Review]]'', September 1, 2002</ref> In order to maintain trade and cultural ties with countries with which it no longer had diplomatic relations, Taiwan established representative offices in these countries, often replacing its former embassies.\n\nBefore the 1990s, the names of these offices would vary considerably from country to country, usually omitting any reference to \"Taiwan\" or \"Republic of China\", instead referring to \"East Asia\", \"Far East\" or \"Free China\".<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mXoFscQ2QwsC&lpg=PA141&ots=JXpnD-DJiQ&dq=centre%20sun%20yat-sen%20luxembourg&pg=PA141#v=onepage&q=centre%20sun%20yat-sen%20luxembourg&f=false ''China and Europe Since 1978: A European Perspective''],  Richard L. Edmonds, Cambridge University Press, 2002, page 141</ref> They would also describe themselves as \"centres\" or \"offices\", concerned with trade, tourism, culture or information, thereby emphasising their private and unofficial status, despite being staffed by [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Taiwan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] personnel.\n\nFor example, in Japan, the former ROC Embassy was replaced by the \"[[Association of East Asian Relations]]\" (AEAR) in 1972.<ref name=\"Mosher\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3YgR77AzwuEC&lpg=PA24&dq=Association%20of%20East%20Asian%20Relations&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q=Association%20of%20East%20Asian%20Relations&f=true International Law of Recognition and the Status of the Republic of China], Hungdah Chiu, in ''The United States and the Republic of China: Democratic Friends, Strategic Allies, and Economic Partners'', Steven W. Mosher\nTransaction Publishers, 1992, page 24</ref> In Malaysia, following the closure of the Consulate General in [[Kuala Lumpur]] in 1974, an office known as the Far East Travel and Trade Centre was established.<ref name=\"Jie Chen\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=moqbJAj2b1kC&pg=PA82&dq=free+china+malaysia+1974+taipei&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj49-3q87fLAhWFdpoKHRBkBkgQ6AEIQjAD#v=onepage&q=free%20china%20malaysia%201974%20taipei&f=false ''Foreign Policy of the New Taiwan: Pragmatic Diplomacy in Southeast Asia''], Jie Chen, Edward Elgar Publishing, 2002, page 82</ref> In the [[Philippines]], the former Embassy in [[Manila]] was replaced by the \"Pacific Economic and Cultural Center\", established in 1975.<ref name=\"Mosher\" /> In [[Thailand]], the former Embassy in [[Bangkok]] was replaced by the \"Office of the Representative of China Airlines\" in 1975.<ref name=\"Samuel C Y Ku\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZUGN8zCUm-AC&lpg=PA263&ots=gcK6dypyJI&dq=taiwan%20Embassy%20in%20Bangkok%20closed%201975&pg=PA263#v=onepage&q=taiwan%20Embassy%20in%20Bangkok%20closed%201975&f=true The Changing Political Economy of Taiwan's and China's Relations with Southeast Asia: A Comparative Perspective], Samuel C Y Ku in ''China and Southeast Asia: Global Changes and Regional Challenge'', Ho Khai Leong, Samuel C Y Ku, Institute of Southeast Asian Studies, 2005, page 259</ref> This was later renamed the Far East Trade Office in 1980.<ref name=\"Jie Chen\" />\n\nIn the United States, Taipei's mission, established in 1979, was known as the \"'''Coordination Council for North American Affairs'''\" (CCNAA).<ref>[http://www.cftc.gov/files/foia/repfoia/foirf0502b010.pdf Memorandum of Understanding between the American Institute in Taiwan and the Coordination Council for North American Affairs on the Exchange of Information Concerning Commodity Futures and Options Matters], Signed at Arlington, Virginia this 11th day of January 1993</ref> As of 2019, it has been renamed \"Taiwan Council for US Affairs.\" <ref>[https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3710503]</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, Taiwan was represented by the \"Free Chinese Centre\", established in 1963.<ref name=\"books.google.co.uk\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wXpwXvjAAkYC&lpg=PA39&ots=a35FcBvEv9&dq=%22Free%20Chinese%20Centre%22%20london&pg=PA39#v=onepage&q=%22Free%20Chinese%20Centre%22%20london&f=false ''The Cold War's Odd Couple: The Unintended Partnership Between the Republic of China and the UK, 1950\u20131958''], Steven Tsang, I.B.Tauris, 2006, page 39</ref> In [[West Germany]], it was represented by a ''B\u00fcro der Fernost-Informationen'' (\"Far East Information Office\") established in 1972.<ref name=\"Vertretung\">[http://www.taiwanembassy.org/ct.asp?xItem=635638&CtNode=53&mp=107&xp1= Die Beziehungen zwischen Taiwan und Deutschland]{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, Taipeh Vertretung in der Bundesrepublik Deutschland</ref> In [[Spain]], the office, established in 1973, was known as the ''Centro Sun Yat-sen'' (\"Sun Yat-sen Centre\").<ref name=\"hibou\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UdsBUEQa6qIC&lpg=PA157&dq=%22Anglo-Taiwan%20Trade%20Committee%22%201976%20visa&pg=PA154#v=onepage&q&f=true Pretence of Privatisation: Taiwan's External Relations], Fran\u00e7oise Mengin, in ''Privatising the State'', B\u00e9atrice Hibou, C. Hurst & Co. Publishers, 2004, pages 154</ref> In the [[Netherlands]], the office was known as the \"Far East Trade Office\".<ref name=\"hibou\" />\n\nHowever, in the late 1980s, these offices began using the name \"Taipei\" in their titles. In May 1992, the AEAR offices in Japan became Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Offices.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0ksYAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Association+of+East+Asian+Relations%22+1992&dq=%22Association+of+East+Asian+Relations%22+1992&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwihtNqP-dXKAhXIOBQKHbJoBBMQ6AEINjAE ''Republic of China Yearbook''] Kwang Hwa Publishing Company, 1998, 145</ref> The \"Free Chinese Centre\" in London was similarly renamed the \"Taipei Representative Office\".<ref>[http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/foreign-affairs/2013/04/10/375637/Former-diplomats.htm Former diplomats to Great Britain remember Thatcher], ''[[The China Post]]'', 10 April 2013</ref> In September 1994, the [[Clinton Administration]] announced that the CCNAA office in Washington could similarly be called the Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office.<ref name=\"Chi Su\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hdTMuHG2hXcC&lpg=PA31&ots=R8qq7zkN9U&dq=%22Coordination%20Council%20for%20North%20American%20Affairs%22%201993%20taipei&pg=PA31#v=onepage&q=%22Coordination%20Council%20for%20North%20American%20Affairs%22%201993%20taipei&f=true ''Taiwan's Relations with Mainland China: A Tail Wagging Two Dogs''], Chi Su\nRoutledge, 2008, page 31</ref>\n[[File:Mlc center syd.jpg|thumb|The building hosting TECO branch office in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]]] \nEarlier in 1989, the \"Pacific Economic and Cultural Center\" in [[Manila]]  became the \"[[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in the Philippines]]\".<ref name=\"Enduring Dynamics\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wFxxAAAAMAAJ&dq=Pacific+Economic+and+Cultural+Center+in+Manila+renamed+Taipei+Economic+and+Cultural+Office+1989&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Taipei+Economic+and+Cultural+Office%22 ''Ensuring Interests: Dynamics of China-Taiwan Relations and Southeast Asia''], Khai Leong Ho, Guozhong He, Institute of China Studies, University of Malaya, 2006, page 25</ref>    In 1991, the \"Taiwan Marketing Service\" office in [[Canberra]], Australia, established in 1988, also became a \"Taipei Economic and Cultural Office\", along with the \"Far East Trading Company\" offices in Sydney and [[Melbourne]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=esT-P4oEkrUC&lpg=PA33&ots=F8Dr06HWVR&dq=taipei%20market%20service%20canberra&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q=taipei%20market%20service%20canberra&f=true ''Australia and China: Partners in Asia''], Colin Mackerras, Macmillan Education, 1996, page 33</ref>\n\nOther names are still used elsewhere; for example, the mission in Moscow is formally known as the \"Representative Office in Moscow for the Taipei-Moscow Economic and Cultural Coordination Commission\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mofa.gov.tw/|title=\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b(\u53f0\u7063)\u5916\u4ea4\u90e8\u5168\u7403\u8cc7\u8a0a\u7db2|first=|last=\u5916\u4ea4\u90e8|date=9 January 2015|website=\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b\u5916\u4ea4\u90e8 - \u5168\u7403\u8cc7\u8a0a\u7db2 Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Republic of China (Taiwan)}}</ref> the mission in New Delhi is known as the \"Taipei Economic and Cultural Center\".<ref>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=128705 MoU between India-Taipei Association (ITA) in Taipei and Taipei Economic and Cultural Center (TECC) in India on cooperation in the field of Micro, Small and Medium Enterprises], Press Information Bureau, Government of India,\nCabinet, 14 October 2015</ref> The mission in [[Pretoria]] is known as the \"Taipei Liaison Office\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roc-taiwan.org/ZA/mp.asp?mp=402|title=\u9996\u9801 - \u99d0\u5357\u975e\u5171\u548c\u570b\u53f0\u5317\u806f\u7d61\u4ee3\u8868\u8655 Taipei Liaison Office in the RSA|first=Internet|last=Team|website=www.roc-taiwan.org}}</ref>\n\nThe two most recent ones to change their official names, in Papua New Guinea and in Jordan, both use the name ''Taipei Economic and Cultural Office'' (Chinese: \u81fa\u5317\u7d93\u6fdf\u6587\u5316\u8fa6\u4e8b\u8655, using the more complicated character for [[Taipei]], \u81fa\u5317, instead of \u53f0\u5317).\n\n==TECRO in the United States==\n{{main|Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in the United States}}\n[[File:Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in the United States from VOA (1).jpg|thumb|[[Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in the United States]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]]]\n\nOriginally called the Coordination Council for North American Affairs (CCNAA), the name of the CCNAA office in Washington, D.C. (the \"[[embassy]]\") was changed to \"Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office\" (TECRO) as a result of the [[Clinton Administration]]'s Taiwan Policy Review of 1994.<ref name=\"Chi Su\" /> Similarly, the names of the twelve other CCNAA offices (\"[[consulate]]s\") in the United States were changed to \"Taipei Economic and Cultural Office\" (TECO).<ref>\"[http://www.fapa.org/generalinfo/TPR1994.html 1994 Taiwan Policy Review].\" ''Formosan Association for Public Affairs''. Retrieved on January 28, 2009.</ref>\n\nOn May 24, 2019, Taiwan informed that \"the Coordination Council for North American Affairs\" was renamed \"the Taiwan Council for U.S. Affairs\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/taiwan-changing-name-of-de-facto-embassy-in-us/2019/05/24/7afc66e8-7e93-11e9-b1f3-b233fe5811ef_story.html?noredirect=on|title=Taiwan changing name of de-facto embassy in US}}</ref>\n\n==TECRO in Japan==\n{{main|Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in Japan}}\n[[File:Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office in Japan 20080811.jpg|thumb|TECRO in [[Japan]]]]\nDiplomatic relations between the Republic of China and Japan were broken off in September 1972. For practical reasons, the Association of East Asian Relations (AEAR), was established two months after the Japan-China Joint Communique was signed. EARA had offices in Taipei, Tokyo, Osaka, and Fukuoka.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3YgR77AzwuEC&lpg=PA24&dq=%22Association%20of%20East%20Asian%20Relations%22&pg=PA24#v=onepage&q=%22Association%20of%20East%20Asian%20Relations%22&f=false The International Law of Recognition and the Status of the Republic of China], Hungdah Chiu in ''The United States and the Republic of China: Democratic Friends, Strategic Allies, and Economic Partners'', Steven W. Mosher, Transaction Publishers, 1992, page 24</ref> In 1992, Japan authorized the change in name of AEAR to TECRO.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0ksYAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Association+of+East+Asian+Relations%22+1992&dq=%22Association+of+East+Asian+Relations%22+1992&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiL_caYnI7LAhXFwBQKHTbjBSEQ6AEIMzAE|title=Republic of China Yearbook|publisher=Kwang Hwa Publishing Company|year=1998|page=145}}</ref>\n\n==Representations in the PRC Special administrative regions==\n===Hong Kong===\n{{main|Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Hong Kong}}\nIn Hong Kong, from 1966, Taiwan was represented by the 'Chung Hwa Travel Service', a name chosen to avoid upsetting Beijing.<ref>[http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2011/07/17/2003508415 Is name change a game changer?], ''[[Taipei Times]]'', 17 July 2011</ref> On 20 July 2011, as a result of warming relations between Taiwan and Beijing, the name was formally changed to the Taipei Economic and Cultural Office, bringing it into line with other Republic of China representative offices around the world.<ref>[http://www.rthk.org.hk/rthk/news/englishnews/news.htm?main&20110715&56&770050 Taiwan changes name of HK office], RTHK News, 15 July 2011</ref>\n\n===Macau===\n{{main|Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Macau}}\n\nIn Macau, from 1989 to 1999, Taiwan was represented by the 'Taipei Trade and Tourism Office', Taiwan's first-time representation in Macau after Kuomintang's expulsion from Macau as the consequence of the [[12-3 incident|December 3rd Incident]] in 1966. From 1999 to 2011, Taiwan was represented by the 'Taipei Economic and Cultural Center'. On 13 May 2012, the name was formally changed to the Taipei Economic and Cultural Office.<ref>[http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/china-taiwan-relations/2012/05/14/341018/Macau-representative.htm Macau representative office in Taiwan opens] ''[[The China Post]]'', May 14, 2012</ref>\n\n==TRO in the United Kingdom==\n{{see also|Taipei Representative Office in the U.K.}}\n\nIn 1950, the UK switched recognition from the Republic of China to the People's Republic of China (PRC) shortly after its establishment, while maintaining the British Consulate in [[Tamsui]], through which the UK continued to carry out consular and trade-related activities. The Consulate was closed after the UK and the PRC upgraded relations to Ambassadorial level in March 1972, and in June 1980 the building and land of the Consulate were returned to the Taiwanese government. The ROC government\u2019s office in the UK was set up in September 1963, and at the time was known as the Free Chinese Centre.<ref name=\"books.google.co.uk\"/> In 1992, this was revised to become the Taipei Representative Office in the UK.<ref>[http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/foreign-affairs/2013/04/10/375637/Former-diplomats.htm Former diplomats to Great Britain remember Thatcher], ''[[China Post]]'', 10 April 2013</ref>\n\n== Taipei Representative Office in Norway ==\n{{Infobox Government agency\n| agency_name = '''Taipei Representative Office in Norway'''<br>\u99d0\u632a\u5a01\u4ee3\u8868\u8655\n| nativename = \n| seal = \n| seal_width = \n| seal_caption = \n| logo = \n| logo_width = \n| logo_caption = \n| formed = 1980 (as Taipei Trade Centre)<ref name=\"hibou\"></ref>\n| preceding1 = \n| preceding2 = \n| dissolved = 30 September 2017\n| superseding = \n| jurisdiction = \n| headquarters = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n| employees = \n| budget = \n| minister1_name = \n| minister1_pfo = \n| chief1_name = \n| chief1_position = \n| chief2_name = \n| chief2_position = \n| parent_agency = \n| child1_agency = \n| child2_agency = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}The '''Taipei Representative Office in Norway'''; ({{zh|c=\u99d0\u632a\u5a01\u4ee3\u8868\u8655|p=Zh\u00f9 Nu\u00f3w\u0113i D\u00e0ibi\u01ceo Ch\u00f9}}) was a diplomatic mission of [[Taiwan]] to [[Norway]] functioned as a [[De facto embassy|''de facto'' embassy]]. The first representative office of Taiwan in Norway was the '''Taipei Trade Centre''', established in 1980.<ref name=\"hibou2\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UdsBUEQa6qIC&lpg=PA157&dq=%22Anglo-Taiwan%20Trade%20Committee%22%201976%20visa&pg=PA154#v=onepage&q=Spain&f=false A Pretence of Privatisation: Taiwan's External Relations], Fran\u00e7oise Mengin, in ''Privatising the State'', B\u00e9atrice Hibou, C. Hurst & Co. Publishers, 2004, pages 154</ref> \n\nIn July 2017, the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Taiwan)|ROC Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] announced that the office will be suspended on 30 September 2017 and affairs related to Taiwanese in the country will be handled by [[Taipei Mission in Sweden]]. The decision was made to improve the efficiency of the [[Foreign relations of Taiwan|foreign diplomatic missions]] of Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/aipl/201707270016.aspx|title=Taiwan suspending operations at 3 overseas offices|last1=Hou|first1=Elaine|date=27 July 2017|publisher=Focus Taiwan|accessdate=28 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Taipei representative offices around the world==\nThe list below shows the countries or regions where TECROs/TROs are established.\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!Country or Region!!Office Name!!Representative!!Website\n|-\n|{{ARG}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Argentina|Oficina Comercial y Cultural de Taipei en Argentina]] || [[Matthew S. Lee]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/AR]\n|-\n|{{AUS}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Australia]] || [[Elliott Charng]] || [https://www.taiwanembassy.org/au_en/index.html]\n|-\n|{{AUT}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Culture Office in Austria]] || [[Vanessa Shih]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/AT]\n|-\n|{{BHR}}|| Taipei Trade Office in the Kingdom of Bahrain || [[Michael Chen (diplomat)|Michael Chen]] || [http://www.mofa.gov.tw/EnMobile/OverseasOffice_Detail.aspx?s=769ACA0A9CA10DF0]\n|-\n|{{BEL}}|| [[Taipei Representative Office in the EU and Belgium]] || [[Tung Kuo-yu]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/BE]\n|-\n|{{BRA}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Brazil|Escrit\u00f3rio Econ\u00f4mico e Cultural de Taipei no Brasil]] || [[Isaac Tsai]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/BR]\n|-\n|{{BRN}}|| Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Brunei Darussalam || [[Andrew Lee (politician)|Andrew Lee]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/BN]\n|-\n|{{CAN}}|| [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Office in Canada]] || [[Kung Chung-chen|Winston Chen]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/CA]\n|-\n|{{CHL}}|| Oficina Econ\u00f3mica y Cultural de Taipei en Chile || [[Wang Ming-wen]] || [http://www.taiwanembassy.org/CL]\n|-\n|{{COL}}|| [[Taipei Commercial Office in Bogot\u00e1, Colombia|Oficina Comercial de Taipei en Bogot\u00e1, Colombia]] || [[Tang Ji-zen]] || [http://www.taiwanembas