{"title_page": "Leo Fernando", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = Hon. Sir\n| name                = Leo Fernando\n| honorific-suffix    = [[CBE]]\n| image               = \n| imagesize           =250px        \n| caption             =\n| order               = \n| order1              = \n| order2              =\n| constituency_MP     = [[Buttala Electoral District|Buttala]]\n| parliament          = Ceylon \n| majority            =\n| term_start          = 1947\n| term_end            = 1954\n| predecessor         = ''Constituency Created''\n| successor           = [[Gladwin Kotelawala]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|df=y|1895|11|18}}\n| birth_name          = Warusahennedige Leo Fernando\n| birth_place         = Pandura, Sri Lanka\n| death_date          =  {{death date and age|df=y|1954|11|30|1895|11|18}}\n| death_place         =  \n| nationality         = Sri Lankan\n| party               = [[United National Party]]\n| otherparty          = \n| spouse              = Irene\n| partner             = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married -->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = \n| occupation          = Businessman\n| profession          =  \n| religion            = \n| rank                = \n| branch              = \n| unit                = \n| allegiance          = \n| serviceyears        = \n| awards              = \n| battles             = \n| signature           =\n| website             =\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Sir Leo Fernando''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|commas=on|CBE}} (18 November 1895 \u2013 30 November 1954) was a [[Ceylon]]ese businessman and politician. He was a member of parliament for the [[Buttala Electoral District]].\n\nWarusahennedige Leo Fernando was born on 18 November 1895. He developed a considerable ownership in the transport sector, having established the Panadura Bus Company and owning transport lorries. He also owned many Tea and Rubber plantations in Ceylon, the Gikiyanakande and Meddegedara estates among them. The Gikiyanakande estate was owned previously by Queen Elizabeth's cousin, [[John Elphinstone, 17th Lord Elphinstone|Lord Elphinstone]]. The signing of the deeds at the time of purchase by Fernando were done at Buckingham Palace in 1950. He also owned significant shareholdings in Associated Motorways (AMW), Central Hospitals and the Southwestern bus company. The Panadura Bus Company was later [[nationalised]] in 1958 to form the [[Ceylon Transport Board]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/081228/FunDay/fundaytimes_2.html|title=When bus services were nationalised|newspaper=[[Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)|Sunday Times]]|date=28 December 2008|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=40010|newspaper=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]]|title=I prepared my own budgets, budget speeches|first=Ravi|last=Ladduwahetty|date=28 November 2011|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> At the time of his death in 1954, Panadura Motor Transit (PMT) owned more than 350 buses, 200 lorries and more than 10,000 acres of tea and rubber plantations, apart from his significant investments in several top companies in Ceylon. He donated the college hall of [[Sri Sumangala College]] in his home town of Panadura.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.island.lk/2010/03/03/features2.html|title=Sri Sumangala College, Panadura, 101 years old|newspaper=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]]|first=Walter|last=Wijenayake|date=3 March 2010|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nFernando was elected to the [[Parliament of Ceylon]] at the [[1947 Ceylonese parliamentary election|1st parliamentary election]] in 1947 representing the [[Buttala Electoral District|Buttala electorate]], securing over 77% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/web/images/pdf/general-election-results/general-election-1947.pdf |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1947 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |accessdate=30 June 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He retained the seat at the subsequent [[1952 Ceylonese parliamentary election|parliamentary election]]s in 1952, with a healthy 70% of the vote<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/web/images/pdf/general-election-results/general-election-1952.pdf |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1952 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |accessdate=30 June 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and remained in parliament until his death in 1954.\n\nHe and wife, Irene, had three daughters and a son. They are Kusumalatha, Mallika, Ranjith and Kanthi. His daughter, [[Mallika de Mel|Mallika]] (member for [[Matara Electoral District|Matara]] (2001\u20132003)), married [[Ronnie de Mel]], a civil servant, member for [[Devinuwara Electoral District|Devinuwara]] (1969\u20131988), member for Matara (1994\u20132000), [[National List Member of Parliament|National List]] member (2001\u20132004) and [[Minister of Finance (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Finance]] (1977\u20131988).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.island.lk/2009/10/16/opinion5.html|title=Mallika Lakshmi De Mel|newspaper=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]]|first=Methsiri|last=Cooray|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nFernando owned a custom built [[Lincoln Cosmopolitan|Ford Lincoln Cosmopolitan]] on which his name was engraved on all the accessories of the car, including the seats. He also owned three [[Rolls-Royce Silver Ghost]]s.\n\nHe was appointed an [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in 1951 and Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (CBE) in the [[1953 New Year Honours]]. The day before his death he was appointed [[Knights Bachelor]] on 29 November 1954<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/40369/supplement/47/data.pdf The London Gazette OF FRIDAY, 3ist DECEMBER, 1954]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Members of 1st Parliament of Ceylon}}\n{{Members of 2nd Parliament of Ceylon}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fernando, Leo}}\n[[Category:Members of the 1st Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Ceylonese knights]]\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ceylonese Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n\n\n{{SriLanka-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = Hon. Sir\n| name                = Leo Fernando\n| honorific-suffix    = [[CBE]]\n| image               = \n| imagesize           =250px        \n| caption             =\n| order               = \n| order1              = \n| order2              =\n| constituency_MP     = [[Buttala Electoral District|Buttala]]\n| parliament          = Ceylon \n| majority            =\n| term_start          = 1947\n| term_end            = 1954\n| predecessor         = ''Constituency Created''\n| successor           = [[Gladwin Kotelawala]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|df=y|1895|11|18}}\n| birth_name          = Warusahennedige Leo Fernando\n| birth_place         = Pandura, Sri Lanka\n| death_date          =  {{death date and age|df=y|1954|11|30|1895|11|18}}\n| death_place         =  \n| nationality         = Sri Lankan\n| party               = [[United National Party]]\n| otherparty          = \n| spouse              = Irene\n| partner             = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married -->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = \n| occupation          = Businessman\n| profession          =  \n| religion            = \n| rank                = \n| branch              = \n| unit                = \n| allegiance          = \n| serviceyears        = \n| awards              = \n| battles             = \n| signature           =\n| website             =\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Sir Leo Fernando''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|commas=on|CBE}} (18 November 1895 \u2013 30 November 1954) was a [[Ceylon]]ese businessman and politician. He was a member of parliament for the [[Buttala Electoral District]].\n\nWarusahennedige Leo Fernando was born on 18 November 1895. He developed a considerable ownership in the transport sector, having established the Panadura Bus Company and owning transport lorries. He also owned many Tea and Rubber plantations in Ceylon, the Gikiyanakande and Meddegedara estates among them. The Gikiyanakande estate was owned previously by Queen Elizabeth's cousin, [[John Elphinstone, 17th Lord Elphinstone|Lord Elphinstone]]. The signing of the deeds at the time of purchase by Fernando were done at Buckingham Palace in 1950. He also owned significant shareholdings in Associated Motorways (AMW), Central Hospitals and the Southwestern bus company. The Panadura Bus Company was later [[nationalised]] in 1958 to form the [[Ceylon Transport Board]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/081228/FunDay/fundaytimes_2.html|title=When bus services were nationalised|newspaper=[[Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)|Sunday Times]]|date=28 December 2008|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=40010|newspaper=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]]|title=I prepared my own budgets, budget speeches|first=Ravi|last=Ladduwahetty|date=28 November 2011|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> At the time of his death in 1954, Panadura Motor Transit (PMT) owned more than 350 buses, 200 lorries and more than 10,000 acres of tea and rubber plantations, apart from his significant investments in several top companies in Ceylon. He donated the college hall of [[Sri Sumangala College]] in his home town of Panadura.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.island.lk/2010/03/03/features2.html|title=Sri Sumangala College, Panadura, 101 years old|newspaper=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]]|first=Walter|last=Wijenayake|date=3 March 2010|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nFernando was elected to the [[Parliament of Ceylon]] at the [[1947 Ceylonese parliamentary election|1st parliamentary election]] in 1947 representing the [[Buttala Electoral District|Buttala electorate]], securing over 77% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/web/images/pdf/general-election-results/general-election-1947.pdf |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1947 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |accessdate=30 June 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He retained the seat at the subsequent [[1952 Ceylonese parliamentary election|parliamentary election]]s in 1952, with a healthy 70% of the vote<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/web/images/pdf/general-election-results/general-election-1952.pdf |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1952 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |accessdate=30 June 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and remained in parliament until his death in 1954.\n\nHe and wife, Irene, had three daughters and a son. They are Kusumalatha, Mallika, Ranjith and Kanthi. His daughter, [[Mallika de Mel|Mallika]] (member for [[Matara Electoral District|Matara]] (2001\u20132003)), married [[Ronnie de Mel]], a civil servant, member for [[Devinuwara Electoral District|Devinuwara]] (1969\u20131988), member for Matara (1994\u20132000), [[National List Member of Parliament|National List]] member (2001\u20132004) and [[Minister of Finance (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Finance]] (1977\u20131988).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.island.lk/2009/10/16/opinion5.html|title=Mallika Lakshmi De Mel|newspaper=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)|The Island]]|first=Methsiri|last=Cooray|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nFernando owned a custom built [[Lincoln Cosmopolitan|Ford Lincoln Cosmopolitan]] on which his name was engraved on all the accessories of the car, including the seats. He also owned three [[Rolls-Royce Silver Ghost]]s.\n\nHe was appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in 1951 and Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (CBE) in the [[1953 New Year Honours]]. The day before his death he was appointed [[Knights Bachelor]] on 29 November 1954<ref>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/40369/supplement/47/data.pdf The London Gazette OF FRIDAY, 3ist DECEMBER, 1954]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Members of 1st Parliament of Ceylon}}\n{{Members of 2nd Parliament of Ceylon}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fernando, Leo}}\n[[Category:Members of the 1st Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Ceylonese knights]]\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ceylonese Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n\n\n{{SriLanka-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "a -> an", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leo_Fernando"}
{"title_page": "Lakshman Jayakody", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB |date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = [[The Honorable|Hon.]]\n| name               = Lakshman Jayakody\n| honorific-suffix   = \n| image              = Lakshman Jayakody.jpg\n| caption            = \n| office             = [[Ministry of Internal Affairs, Wayamba Development and Cultural Affairs#Ministers|Minister of Cultural and Religious Affairs]]\n| term_start         = 1994\n| term_end           = 2000\n| president          = [[Chandrika Kumaratunga]]\n| primeminister      = [[Sirimavo Bandaranaike]]\n| predecessor        = [[W. J. M. Lokubandara]]\n| successor          = [[Monty Gopallawa]]\n| constituency_MP2   = [[Gampaha Electoral District|Gampaha District]]\n| parliament2        = Sri Lanka\n| term_start2        = 1989\n| term_end2          = 2000\n| constituency_MP3   = [[Attanagalla Electoral District|Attanagalla]]\n| parliament3        = Sri Lanka\n| term_start3        = 1980\n| term_end3          = 1989\n| predecessor3       = [[Sirimavo Bandaranaike]]\n| successor3         = ''Constituency Abolished''\n| constituency_MP4   = [[Divulapitiya Electoral District|Divulapitiya]]\n| parliament4        = Ceylon\n| term_start4        = 1960\n| term_end4          = 1977\n| predecessor4       = Percy Jayakodi\n| successor4         = Ariyaratne Jayatillake\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1930|08|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = Sri Lanka\n| nationality        = [[Sri Lanka]]n\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2010|08|30|1930|08|24|df=yes}}\n| party              = [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]]\n| otherparty         = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| alma_mater         = [[Trinity College, Kandy|Trinity College]], [[Ananda College]]\n| occupation         =\n| profession         = \n| signature          =\n| residence          = \n| website            = \n| footnotes          =\n}}\n\n'''Lakshman Jayakody''' (24 August 1930 &ndash; 30 August 2010) was a Sri Lankan politician, an [[SLFP]] [[stalwart (politics)|stalwart]] and the [[Cabinet Minister|Minister]] of Cultural and Religious Affairs in the [[Sri Lanka]]n [[Cabinet of Sri Lanka|Cabinet]] from 1994 to 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultural.gov.lk/history/history.htm |title=History / The Birth of Ministry of Cultural Affairs and National Heritage |publisher=Ministry of National Heritage and Cultural Affairs |location=Sri Lanka) |accessdate=30 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617140706/http://www.cultural.gov.lk/history/history.htm |archivedate=17 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\nLakshman Jayakody was born 24 August 1930 the eldest child of Lionel Jayakody and Gwendoline. He commenced his education at [[Ladies' College, Colombo]], where his mother was educated, before the family moved to [[Kandy]], when he was admitted [[Trinity College (Kandy)|Trinity College]]. Later he gained admission to [[Ananda College]], [[Colombo]] to do advance level studies, where he also represented the college XI cricket team and won colours in cricket.\n\nJayakody joined the Sri Lanka Freedom Party (SLFP) on 1 November 1954, and became the General Secretary of the SLFP Trade Union in 1959. In July 1960 he contested the [[July 1960 Ceylonese parliamentary election|5th general parliamentary elections]] in the [[Divulapitiya Electoral District|Divulapitiya electorate]]. He was successful, winning the seat by almost 5,000 votes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/web/images/pdf/general-election-results/parliamentary-general-election-1960-07-20.pdf |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 20 July 1960 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |accessdate=27 May 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Jayakody retained the seat in the two subsequent elections but lost it in the [[1977 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|1977 elections]], to the [[United National Party]] candidate, [[Ariyaratne Jayatillake]], by 2,874 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/web/images/pdf/general-election-results/general-election-1977.pdf|title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1977 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |accessdate=27 May 2017}}</ref> During this period he served as the Deputy Minister of Defence and Foreign Affairs and the Parliamentary Secretary to the Prime Minister in the [[Second Sirimavo Bandaranaike cabinet]].\n\nJayakody selected as the Sri Lanka Freedom Party's representative for [[Attanagalla Electoral District|Attanagalla]], replacing [[Sirimavo Bandaranaike]] after she was expelled from parliament and banned from public office for seven years in 1980.\n\nAt the [[1989 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|9th parliamentary election]]s in 1989 he successfully contested the [[Gampaha Electoral District|Gampaha electorate]]. Jayakody retained his seat at the [[1994 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] in 1994 and was appointed [[Ministry of Internal Affairs, Wayamba Development and Cultural Affairs#Ministers|Minister of Cultural and Religious Affairs]]. He did not contest the elections in 2000, retiring from politics.\n\nHe subsequently served as a senior presidential advisor to the [[President of Sri Lanka|President]] [[Chandrika Kumaratunga]] and President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2008/06/29/spe09.asp | title=True love finds a second chance | date=29 June 2008 | newspaper=Sunday Observer | location=Sri Lanka | first=Lakmal | last=Welabada | accessdate=30 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011141150/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2008/06/29/spe09.asp | archivedate=11 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nJayakody died at [[Colombo General Hospital]] on 30 August 2010, at age 80.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/08/31/news13.asp | title=Death of former Minister Lakshman Jayakody | newspaper=Daily News | location=Sri Lanka | date=31 August 2010 | accessdate=30 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903125147/http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/08/31/news13.asp | archivedate=3 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100905193626/http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/09/02/news12.asp Lakshman Jayakody, tower of strength to SLFP]\n\n{{Members of the 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 8th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 7th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 6th Parliament of Ceylon}}\n{{Members of the 5th Parliament of Ceylon}}\n{{Members of the Sri Lankan Parliament from Gampaha}}\n{{Members of the Sri Lankan Parliament from Attanagalla}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jayakody, Lakshman}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the 5th Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Members of the 6th Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Members of the 7th Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 8th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Kandy]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary secretaries of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Culture ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n\n\n{{SriLanka-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{EngvarB |date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = [[The Honorable|Hon.]]\n| name               = Lakshman Jayakody\n| honorific-suffix   = \n| image              = Lakshman Jayakody.jpg\n| caption            = \n| office             = [[Ministry of Internal Affairs, Wayamba Development and Cultural Affairs#Ministers|Minister of Cultural and Religious Affairs]]\n| term_start         = 1994\n| term_end           = 2000\n| president          = [[Chandrika Kumaratunga]]\n| primeminister      = [[Sirimavo Bandaranaike]]\n| predecessor        = [[W. J. M. Lokubandara]]\n| successor          = [[Monty Gopallawa]]\n| constituency_MP2   = [[Gampaha Electoral District|Gampaha District]]\n| parliament2        = Sri Lanka\n| term_start2        = 1989\n| term_end2          = 2000\n| constituency_MP3   = [[Attanagalla Electoral District|Attanagalla]]\n| parliament3        = Sri Lanka\n| term_start3        = 1980\n| term_end3          = 1989\n| predecessor3       = [[Sirimavo Bandaranaike]]\n| successor3         = ''Constituency Abolished''\n| constituency_MP4   = [[Divulapitiya Electoral District|Divulapitiya]]\n| parliament4        = Ceylon\n| term_start4        = 1960\n| term_end4          = 1977\n| predecessor4       = Percy Jayakodi\n| successor4         = Ariyaratne Jayatillake\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1930|08|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = Sri Lanka\n| nationality        = [[Sri Lanka]]n\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2010|08|30|1930|08|24|df=yes}}\n| party              = [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]]\n| otherparty         = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| alma_mater         = [[Trinity College, Kandy|Trinity College]], [[Ananda College]]\n| occupation         =\n| profession         = \n| signature          =\n| residence          = \n| website            = \n| footnotes          =\n}}\n\n'''Lakshman Jayakody''' (24 August 1930 &ndash; 30 August 2010)  was a Sri Lankan politician, an [[SLFP]] [[stalwart (politics)|stalwart]] and the [[Cabinet Minister|Minister]] of Cultural and Religious Affairs in the [[Sri Lanka]]n [[Cabinet of Sri Lanka|Cabinet]] from 1994 to 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cultural.gov.lk/history/history.htm |title=History / The Birth of Ministry of Cultural Affairs and National Heritage |publisher=Ministry of National Heritage and Cultural Affairs |location=Sri Lanka) |accessdate=30 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617140706/http://www.cultural.gov.lk/history/history.htm |archivedate=17 June 2010 }}</ref>\n\nLakshman Jayakody was born 24 August 1930 the eldest child of Lionel Jayakody and Gwendoline. He commenced his education at [[Ladies' College, Colombo]], where his mother was educated, before the family moved to [[Kandy]], when he was admitted [[Trinity College (Kandy)|Trinity College]]. Later he gained admission to [[Ananda College]], [[Colombo]] to do advance level studies, where he also represented the college XI cricket team and won colours in cricket.\n\nJayakody joined the Sri Lanka Freedom Party (SLFP) on 1 November 1954, and became the General Secretary of the SLFP Trade Union in 1959. In July 1960 he contested the [[July 1960 Ceylonese parliamentary election|5th general parliamentary elections]] in the [[Divulapitiya Electoral District|Divulapitiya electorate]]. He was successful, winning the seat by almost 5,000 votes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/web/images/pdf/general-election-results/parliamentary-general-election-1960-07-20.pdf |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 20 July 1960 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |accessdate=27 May 2017 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Jayakody retained the seat in the two subsequent elections but lost it in the [[1977 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|1977 elections]], to the [[United National Party]] candidate, [[Ariyaratne Jayatillake]], by 2,874 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/web/images/pdf/general-election-results/general-election-1977.pdf|title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1977 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |accessdate=27 May 2017}}</ref> During this period he served as the Deputy Minister of Defence and Foreign Affairs and the Parliamentary Secretary to the Prime Minister in the [[Second Sirimavo Bandaranaike cabinet]].\n\nJayakody selected as the Sri Lanka Freedom Party's representative for [[Attanagalla Electoral District|Attanagalla]], replacing [[Sirimavo Bandaranaike]] after she was expelled from parliament and banned from public office for seven years in 1980.\n\nAt the [[1989 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|9th parliamentary election]]s in 1989 he successfully contested the [[Gampaha Electoral District|Gampaha electorate]]. Jayakody retained his seat at the [[1994 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] in 1994 and was appointed [[Ministry of Internal Affairs, Wayamba Development and Cultural Affairs#Ministers|Minister of Cultural and Religious Affairs]]. He did not contest the elections in 2000, retiring from politics.\n\nHe subsequently served as a senior presidential advisor to the [[President of Sri Lanka|President]] [[Chandrika Kumaratunga]] and President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2008/06/29/spe09.asp | title=True love finds a second chance | date=29 June 2008 | newspaper=Sunday Observer | location=Sri Lanka | first=Lakmal | last=Welabada | accessdate=30 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011141150/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2008/06/29/spe09.asp | archivedate=11 October 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nJayakody died at [[Colombo General Hospital]] on 30 August 2010, at age 80.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/08/31/news13.asp | title=Death of former Minister Lakshman Jayakody | newspaper=Daily News | location=Sri Lanka | date=31 August 2010 | accessdate=30 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903125147/http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/08/31/news13.asp | archivedate=3 September 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100905193626/http://www.dailynews.lk/2010/09/02/news12.asp Lakshman Jayakody, tower of strength to SLFP]\n\n{{Members of the 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 8th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 7th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 6th Parliament of Ceylon}}\n{{Members of the 5th Parliament of Ceylon}}\n{{Members of the Sri Lankan Parliament from Gampaha}}\n{{Members of the Sri Lankan Parliament from Attanagalla}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jayakody, Lakshman}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the 5th Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Members of the 6th Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Members of the 7th Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 8th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Kandy]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary secretaries of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Culture ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n\n\n{{SriLanka-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:DATEUNIFY audit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakshman_Jayakody"}
